04380nam a22006855i 9781463244781DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20222022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2022051987  a97814632447817 a10.31826/97814632447812doi  a(DE-B1597)645296  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aDS35.67.T23bM37 2023 4aDS35.67.T23bM37 2023 7aREL0410002bisacsh04a909/.09767223/eng/202210281 aMårtensson, Ulrika, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAl-Ṭabarī’s madhhab jarīrī :bA Paradigm of Natural Law and Natural Rights for the ʿAbbasid Caliphate /cUlrika Mårtensson. 1aPiscataway, NJ : bGorgias Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (422 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aIslamic History and Thought ;v3000tFrontmatter -- tTABLE OF CONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Markers of Polity: Religion, Philosophy & Law -- tChapter Two. Qur’anic Language, Rhetoric and Composition -- tChapter Three. Natural Law, Natural Rights, and al-Ṭabarī’s madhhab jarīrī -- tChapter Four. al-Ṭabarī’s Methodology -- tChapter Five. Covenant as Grand Theory -- tChapter Six. Concluding Analysis -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe book analyses the works of Muḥammad b. Jarīr al-Ṭabarī (224/839–310/923) as expressions of the theory of natural law and natural rights, and its corollary theories of politics and social contract, language and rhetoric, hermeneutics, metaphysics, ontology, epistemology, and ethics. Through this approach, the author argues that al-Ṭabarī’s scholarship constitutes not only sources of information about the rise and early development of Islam and Islamic polities and disciplines, but theoretically informed analysis of sources and scripture as well. As such, al-Ṭabarī’s works offer important contributions to current research into early Islamic history, law, administration, and the Qur’an. A preliminary effort is also made to historically trace al-Ṭabarī’s theoretical paradigms to a continuum of translation and commentary on Aristotle’s works. The starting point is the mid-500s CE in the Sassanid empire and the Arab polities within its domain, i.e., the Lakhmid kingdom and its administrative links with Hijaz, and the end point is the mid-300s H/900s CE in the Abbasid Caliphate. Alongside this theoretical legacy, the author plots both the Qur’an and al-Ṭabarī’s works, including his famous Qur’an commentary. Special attention is also devoted to relations between theory and practice, concerning ownership of lands, the land tax, redistribution and the common good, conditions for agriculture, and peasants’ rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aAbbasidsxHistoriography. 4aIslam. 4aKoran & Sacred Writings. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Islam / Koran & Sacred Writings.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertGorgias Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076710040uhttps://doi.org/10.31826/978146324478140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781463244781423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781463244781/original  a978-3-11-076710-0  Gorgias Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK